{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_moser_ver01/data/sn85025371/00542867322/1930092501/0732.xml":{"full_text":"The Clarke Courier\nR. N. Dorsey, Publisher\nEstablished in 1861) l\u00bby Capt. Win. N.\nNelson; owned anti edited by the\nlate John O. Crown anti Joseph\nW. Crown for more I bun 33 years.\nEntered at the Postolilce al. Berry\nsille, Vu., us second-class mail mat\nter.\n\nV 31.50 Per l\u2019ear In Advance\nPORSPECT$ GOOD\nDiscussing, in a syndicated article\nthe current political situation, Mark\nSullivan, a closely observing public\nist suggests that the Congressional\nelections this fall will determine the\ntrend of the Presidential campaign\nof 1932. This has always been the\ncase, he points out from a long study\nof \u2018\u2018off-year\u201d elections, and '.it ap\npears likely to follow at this time as\nwell.\nFrom another source we read that j\nthe Democrats are Ifkely to win con-;\ntrol of the H ouse, needing but 53\nseats to do so and having 50 fairly\ncertain in the coming campaigns.\nShould the Democrats gain con- j\ntr^of one or both houses of Con-1\ngress. Mr. Sullivan says, conjecture J\nwould run rife, discussion \u201cwould j\nseethe\u201d. These questions, he feels,\nwould be bandied about:\n\u201cWhat will the Democrats do with\ntheir power? Will they revise the\ntariff dowrnw~ard? If so, will Presi\ndent Hoover veto their action?\n\n\u201cTo turn to another series of j\nspeculations that would boil through\nNovember, if the Democrats should\nwin,\u201d he continues, \u2018\u2018would it follow j\nthat the Democrats w\u2019ould win the\npresidential election two years later? j\nWhom would they nominate? Ex-j\nGovernor Smith? Governor Frank\nlin Roosevelt? Ex-Governor Byrd\nof Virginia?\u201d\nThat little suggestion may be but\na straw, but it is one of the proverb\nbial wisps that indicate how the\nwind of political thought is wafting.\nOf the three names casually dropped\ninto this speculative discussion, one\nis that of Harry F. Byrd.\n-0-\u2014\nRED CROSS ROLL CALL j\nCHAIRMAN APPOINTED j\nBy the appointment of Mrs. Maria j\nLewis, chairman of the Red Cross\nChapter of Clarke county. Rev. T. C.\nPage will have charge of the Roll j\nCall beginning on Armistice Day.\nNovember 11th.\nMr. Page is beginning to form his\ncommittees ond will be prepared\nsoon to make some announcements\nabout the work.\nAN APPEAL\nI appeal to the white people ol\nthis community to give from a quar\nter to a dollar, and to Influence\ntheir children to forego a movie, an\nice cream cone or a package of chew\ning gum and to give from a nickel\nto a quarter towards paying for the\nchairs and other furnishings for the\nsplendid new Manual Training build\ning for the young Negroes of Clarke\nCounty who have come after those\nwho served our ancestors for gener\nations before the War Between the\nStates.\nDon\u2019t you think we should help\nthe race to help themselves? All\npraise to the resident though not a\nnative who helped them to buy the\nland. Don\u2019t let us let Mr. Rosen\nwald or Mr. DuPont of the North do\nit all.\nWhatever is intrusted to me I\nwill place in the hand of the princi\npal, of the school, Rev, E. T. John\nson, a man of great energy and fine\nqualities as a preacher to ann a lead\ner of his people. He has worked for\neight years to obtain this building.\nThe friend and well wisher of all\nNegroes, especially those of Clarke\nCounty. f\nMRS. A. MOORE, JR.\n(Charles Town, W. Va. and Win\nchester, Va. papers please copy).\n\u2018\u2018OLE MISS\u201d\nYou never knowed \u201cold Miss\u201d, you\nsay?\nWell, that\u2019s a pitys sure\nDe kind o\u2019 quality she was\nIs gone forevermore.\nHer gracious speech was like a\nqueen\u2019s,\nSo solf, and yea so strong\nWe all kept time t oher solf voice\nLike marching ao a song.\nA nigger never dared to die\nOr marry on our place,\nWiddout we ask\u2019d her blessing\nHer 'pinion on de case.\nShe knowed more \u2019n de preachers\nCause God showed her how to live\nShe knowed more \u2019n de doctors\nCause God told her what to give.\nDat ole plantation\u2014it wos run\nOn \u2019rangements \u2019bout like dis\nDe place\u2014it b\u2019longed to Master\nBut ole Master b\u2019longed to Miss.\nNow she is gone forever\nAnd what is we to do?\nJes try an\u2019 try to remember\nAnd to do what she say do.\nAnd the Lord will see you thru\nDot\u2019s sure\u2014You try.\n_n-\u2014\nFOR SALE\nSmall house in good repair. Nice\nsized lot and garden. Located on\n^ice Street. Priced to sell. Easy\nerms. Owned by Miss Rose More\nPUK|\nRALPH N. DORSEY\nReal Estate\nBorryvillc, Va.\n\u201cCuss-the-Editor\" Week\nDown at Kerville, Texas, the edi\ntor of the local paper advertised a\n\"Cuss-the-Eaitor week,\u2019 whereby\neverybody wbo wanted to \u2018\u2018eus&\u2019\u2019 tbe\neditor. Could do so a certain week,\nand all tbe \"Ouss-the-iSditor\u201d arti\ncles would be publisned, provided\nthe party doing tne cussing would\nsign his name. He failed to get any\nletters to publish \u201ccussing him.\nThen the editor extended the \u201cCuss\ntne islmtor week indetinitely, and as\na result he received the following\nand only letter.\nDear Sir:\nYou aint so gol darn smart that\nyou can ketch me with your tricks. I\nmay be a dam fool but 1 know better\nthan get in jail for ritin a cussing\nletter threw the males.\n\u2018\u2018In the first place a week ain\u2019t\nenuf to cuss a editur. And in* the\n2nd place I can\u2019t rite like I can cuss.\n\u201cI get mad every time 1 see yur\ndam paper and would Quit you but\nthe old woman would want a tella\nfone put in and it costs to dam\nmuch.\n\u201cWhat for you put it in the paper\nabout ipy boy getting throd in jail?\n1 He didn't do nothing and you know\ni it. He was Kew Klucked. I say to\nhell with you and all the Kew Klucks\n\u201cAnd that time i had a flte with\nmy nabor he didn\u2019t lick me like1'you\nsaid he did. You are a lying?\nYou know what i mean. That\u2019s the\nwajpyou editurs cuss.\n\u2018\u2018You dam editurs is all alike.'You\nprint the bad news and leave out the\nrest. You sure, dident say anything\nwhen my dotter ran off and goi nVar\nried ner when i bott my new car. Np,\nI i gess not.\nI \u201cYou are a hell of a feller you are'\nj\nj \u201cIf ther is any open season for\nj editurs let me know and ill be wate\ning for you.\"\u2014Shepherdstown Reg\nj ister.\n\u2014-0\u2019\u2014\ni HAPPIER HOMES\nMADE BY COLOR\nl\nThe woman\u2019s happiness and good\ni spirits are affected by the \"color\nj schemes in her home is the opinion\nj of leading interior decorators. <\u2018The\nj selection of the right color scheme\nfor a room or to meet the taste of\nthe owner is often a puzzle to our\ncustomers,\u201d said Mr. F. H. Morris.\n\u201cThis is because many people are\nnot acquainted with color and do\nI not realize the effect of different\n(colors upon the feelings and moods'.\ni \u201cFor instance, certain colors are\ni known as warm colors, among which\nare red, ornge, yellow and purple,\ni The cool colors are blue, green, gray\nand lavender.\n\u201cThus in rooms facing the north\nand east, red an dyellow can be used\nto advantage. In rooms facing the\nsouth and Avert, bjue and green aro\nmore desirable. The use of such\ncolors will bring life and cheer into\ndull rooms and mellow daylight in\nsunny rooms.\nNOTICE v\nThe Board of Equalisation of Real\nEstote Assessments adjourned on\ni Friday, September 19th, 1930, to\nmeet again on Monday, October 13th\n1930.\nBerryville, Va.\nSeptember 19th, 1930\nTO WHOM IT MAY CONCERN:\nYou are hereby notified that the\nBoard of Equalization of Rear^Es*\ntate Assessments for the County of\nClarke, will meet at the office of R.\nE. Reid, Commissioner of the Reve\nnue, in Berryville,* Va., od Monday,\nOctober 13, 1830 and will sit there\nI after from day to day and time to\ntime as may be necessary to com\nplete its work, with the exception of\nSaturdays of each week. Such sit-'\ntings shall be for the purpose of\nequalising real estate assessments in\nsaid County and for the purpose of\nhearing all complaints of, inequali\nties Including errors in acreage' In\n.such real estate assessments.\nJ H. BELL, Chairman'\nI F H PIKRt\u00ae, Secretary 1\nA Copy\u2014\nI Teste: EUGENE GLOVER, Clerk\nn\u2014\nPUBLIC SALE\nHaving decided to discontinue\nfarming, I will sell at the Sommer\nville Farm, in White Post, Clarke\ncounty, the following personal prop\nerty, on\nI\nWEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 8, 1030\nbeginning at 10 A. M.\n4 horses, good ones, will work\n[\"anywhere; 3 cows and 2 heifers, 28\nj hogs, implements, machinery, and\nother articles found on a well equip\nped farm.\nTERMS: 12 months, Boyce State\nBank,\nFRANK ROYSTON.\nColeman Dunn, Auctioneer\nG\u00ab*o. H Morgan, Clerk.\n9-25 2t\n\nPUBLIC SALE\nOF HOUSEHOLD AND KITCHEN\nFURNITURE\nI\ni SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 27\nbeginning at 1 P. M.\nHousehold and kitchen furniture,\ntools of all kinds, 6 H. P. Gas En\ngine and wood saw on truck, in good\nshape, and .many other articles.\ni H H STICKLES\n--a-\u2014\nWANTED\nBoarders or to rent heated rooms,\nj separately or for light housekeeping\nMRS. W. S. Carper, Liberty St\nIt pd l\nPERSONALS\nMiss Louise Huyette .returned\nI Monday to Fredericksburg State\nTeachers\u2019 College where she will r\u00ab\nsume her course. Her mother, Mrs.\nJohn H. Huyette, and /Mr. R. E.\nDavis accompanied her.\nMr. Ralph Tupis, wife children\nand sister. Miss Ruth Tunis, of\nButte, Montana, and Miss Cunning\nham, of Washington, spent the week\nend at Horseshoe Lodge.\nMiss Margaret Held and Ruth\nAustin, of Walter Reed Hospital,\nWashington, were guests last week\nof Mr. and Mrs. Howard Locke.\nI I\nMisses Frances and Doris Reid\nJolliffe spent the week end at .Cul\npeper and Richmond. j\nMr. and Mrs. O. A. Lloyd gave\na. dinner party.recently in honor of\ntheir daughter and son-in-law, Mr.\nand Mrs. Edward L. Moyer, who\nwere married on the 18th.\nf..\u2018 n S'' A\nMr. M. F. Payne and boh, Wil\nliam recently visited the former\u2019s\nmother. Mrs. J. D. Foster, of Clar\nendon, Va.\nMr. and Mrs. Bdgar Price, 0f\nSchenectady, N. Y., and Mr. and\nMrs, Clifton Price spent last Wed\nnesday in Charlottesville, Va.\nMr. and' Mrs. Bdgar Price have\nreturned to Schenectady, N. Y., af\nter a visit to Mr. and Mrs. Clifton\nPrice at \u201cSoldier\u2019s Rest.\u201d\n\u2014:-o\nSterling-Shindledecker\nA marriage license was Issued in\nthe Clerk\u2019s Office here last Saturday\nto Mr. Leonard Barnes Sterling, of\nHagerstown, Md., and Miss Evelyn\nNaomi Shindledecker, of Waynes\nboro, Pa. The former is a son of\nMr. Leonard F. Sterling and the\nlatter a daughter of Mr. John W. Q.\nShindledecker. They were married\nin Berryville,\nTEN YEARS AGO\n\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK was poor\nthe markets were erratic and unemploy\nment was on the increase. At that time\nour advice was to avoid becoming pani\ncky, to work and to save, looking forward\nto the inevitable readjustment that must\nfollow.\nTODAY our advice is the same.\nTHE v\nFirst National Bank\ns of Berryvilie\nPUBLIC AUCTION\nOF\n\nIn order to reduce our stock we will sell at public auction at the\nBATTLETOWN INN LAWN BERRYVILLE, VA.\n*4It*, u ij\u2019:\n\nSATURDAY, OGT. 4, 1930 Beginning at 1 p.m.\nA v r :\\y. V\nTHE FOLLOWING FURNITURE BOTH NEW SECOND HAND:\nNew Bed Room Suites, Chairs, Rockers. New Overstuffed Suites, Tables, Lamps, Rugs, New Dining-Room Suites, Kitchen Cabinets,\nRefrigerators, Oil Stoves, Gasoline Range, Glass Ware, Pictures, 2 Radios, in perfect condition, one a battery set other electric; 1 Phono\ngraph, and other articles. r n\nai\ni\nI\n1 s V '5 r\nTERMS:\u2014All sums under $10, cash; over that amount a credit of 4 months will be given, purchaser to execute satisfactory endorsed\nnote, bearing interest from date and payable at any of the neighboring banks. ,:u\nc m. Fane, A\u00bbt\nJ. F. SPATES, Clerk","height":"30252","width":"20520"}}
